  <div class="prose">
    <h2>In the Chain</h2>
    <p>The Distressor sits third in the outboard chain, after the WA76. It handles the guitar signal on Channel B — the 1176 catches transients, and the Distressor shapes the sustain and adds harmonic density. It is not in the vocal chain by default but gets patched in for aggressive vocal sounds.</p>

    <h2>Controls</h2>
    <p>Guitar tracking runs at 4:1 with medium attack, medium-fast release. The DIST and BRIT modes stay off for clean tracking — they are for mixdown experiments and re-amping passes. The high-pass sidechain filter is engaged to prevent low-frequency pumping from palm mutes. The GR meter should show 3-6dB of reduction on sustained notes.</p>

    <h2>Character</h2>
    <p>The Distressor is the most flexible compressor in the rack. Eight ratio settings from gentle 1:1 through brick-wall NUKE. The DIST button adds second-harmonic warmth (tape-like), BRIT mode adds third-harmonic edge (tube-like), and stacking both gets you into deliberate saturation territory. NUKE ratio is not a ratio — it is a distortion effect that happens to compress. Used sparingly, it makes a guitar sound like it is being played through a wall.</p>
  </div>
